postcontent:
A rare and beautiful rifle chambered for a superb long-range cartridge. Price includes rifle and scope bases/rings, but not the Burris scope.

This rifle was a competitor of Weatherby back in the 70s, and is chambered for the 7mm Apollo Mach IV cartridge. It's in excellent condition with a bright and shiny bore, original finish on the wood and Duracoated metal for complete rust resistance.

This is a wildcat caliber that is very easy to handload. Take a 300 Winchester Magnum case, neck it down to 7mm with a 7mm neck sizer (I'll supply the Hornady die to do this), and you're ready to load powder, primer and bullet. The manufacturer's printed data (I still have the owner's handbook) claims 3400 fps with a 140 grain bullet!

The Voere action and barrel is noted for extreme strength and accuracy. It was used in the Kleinguenther K-15 which had a 1/2" accuracy guarantee!

It's not like people are buying ammo because they don't have firearms.

You are viewing a Herters Single six in 401 calibre. Markings read "HERTER'S SINGLE SIX .401 CALIBRE" on the ejector side of the barrel, and on the other side of the barrel it reads "HERTER'S WASECA MINN. USA - MADE IN WESTERN GERMANY" Serial number is V20XX. This may have been made by Sauer, but I dont know for sure. Of course this is single action only.

There are some irregularities in the bluing on the grip straps, which I have tried to picture. While the last owner did not mention it, it could be he touched it up with cold blue, or maybe its just some irregularities associated with age and wear, etc. The picture is probably a bit worse than reality, which was why I chose that one so hopefully no surprises. You can be the judge. I will post a few pictures here, and a lot more on the photobucket link. The gun is not perfect, but I believe it is an overall very nice example of this powerful revolver.

*It will come with approximately 220 unprimed brass cases, approx 33 wadcutters, roughly 95 or 100 semi wad cutters, approx 48 round balls, and another 43 semiwadcutters that you see in the red box, in addition to a few spent shells. The owner told me the only reloads were the ones in the red plastic box but not being a reloader, I cant really tell by looking at them. He has owned this and several other guns, most of them bought in the 60's and 70's, so there is a chance he has forgotten which ones were factory, etc. On the other hand, he is pretty sharp for his age so I don't personally doubt him much. Ammo has been in storage for years (if not decades!) and so the boxes show some wear. Some of the rounds may show corrosion or residue on the brass. If this concerns you, contact me and we can dig deeper into condition of ammo. I am also including a Herter's holster and belt. I would describe the holster as functional, but relatively low grade leather. The cartridge loops are too small for the 401 and I am not sure what size they are for. If its a concern let me know and I will try to plug some bullets in it and see what fits.

MUZZELITE BULLPUP RIFLE STOCK

The most striking feature of the MUZZELITE bullpup stock, when attached to your action, is the overall length of 26-1/2". This allows you to carry the rifle with much greater mobility. postcontent:
*Note - the legislation has passed committee and is going to vote on Tuesday (Feb 19) which will ban all hi-capacity magazines in Colorado. Private parties will also no longer be allowed to sell or purchase firearms without a background check after that as well. It is certain to be passed with a Democrat-controlled state congress. These magazines will quadruple in value as they did during the Clinton-era assault weapons ban, and Coloradans will no longer be able to purchase them, much the same as in New York or California.

Saiga .308. Has the rarer and no longer-manufactured lightweight wood furniture. Barrel length is 16" which is stiffer and more accurate than the 21" version. Comes with the following:

3x 25 round hi-cap magazines.
4x 8 round hunting-legal magazines.

6x42 illuminated rangefinding rifle scope with rubber lense covers and rail mount.
http://www.outdoorbunker.com/6-X-42-COMPACT-RANGEFINDER-SCOPE-p/%28ncs-straq642g-%29.htm

KVAR quick detach side-rail optic mount with mil-std rail
http://www.k-var.com/shop/Scope-Mounts/

Tech-sights rear-aperture HK-style sight and receiver buffer. Faster target acquisition, and much more accurate than standard AK sights.
http://www.tech-sights.com/ak.htm

OD sling

Additional side-rail optics mount, with top and side rails.
http://www.cheaperthandirt.com/product/AKS-006

Original receiver cover.


This functions flawlessly. There is roughly 500 rounds through it, without a single FTF or FTE. With good ammo, using the scope, it is capable of 1.5 inch groups at 100 yards. The only issue is that the front hand guard is a little loose. These are no longer for sale at any retailer, and are going to be on the immediate list of banned guns if the AWB passes by spring. If this does not sell, I have no problem keeping it as an investment.

Am open to trades for modern handguns, rifles, and revolvers, but I do not want your old military surplus clunkers, your hi-points, your single-action revolvers, or your 9mm ammo that you think is worth 50 cents a round.
